  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Frameworks\n- Countries are expected to implement consistent anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Harmonization of legal definitions and criminal provisions\n- Mutual legal assistance mechanisms\n\n3. Reporting and Information Sharing\n- International cooperation between financial intelligence units\n- Cross-border reporting requirements\n- Standardized suspicious transaction reporting protocols\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Extradition agreements\n- Asset seizure and recovery processes\n- Coordinated international investigations\n\n5. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Mandatory screening and risk assessment procedures\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Coordinated economic pressure\n- Potential exclusion from global financial systems\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering across national boundaries.",
